WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.900
Hey, thank you everyone so much for coming to see my talk, and let's dive right in.

00:00:04.900 --> 00:00:09.500
That will be my only water-related pun for this talk.

00:00:09.500 --> 00:00:14.000
Okay, so how would you build a sandcastle?

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:20.299
You could make it really simple, you could make it really complex, lots of turrets and all kinds of interesting things on it,

00:00:20.299 --> 00:00:26.200
but all sandcastles have something in common. Eventually, the waves are going to get them.

00:00:26.200 --> 00:00:31.600
So how can we give ourselves some extra time to make our sandcastles last?

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:37.900
We could add a moat that'll buy us some time as the tide comes up. Materials matter as well.

00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:43.700
If we use loose, dry sand, that is not going to last as long as if we use something a bit sturdier,

00:00:43.700 --> 00:00:50.500
like these kids may have used concrete for theirs. But how do we know what's going to happen to our sandcastle?

00:00:50.500 --> 00:01:00.000
How can we provide something that is going to protect it from all of the many things that can happen to sand-based structures on water?

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.200
So I'd like to introduce you to hydrodynamic modeling.

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:12.400
This is a way where we can make the sandcastle, the waves, the surface, the conditions, the wind, all of it numerically.

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:17.400
So this technology is already being used across Washington State, here where we are,

00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:23.599
where shoreline change is just a part of life for a lot of our coastal communities.

00:01:23.599 --> 00:01:33.099
So Washington State has about 3,026 miles of coastline. We have a vertical tidal range of about 13 feet in some areas.

00:01:33.099 --> 00:01:40.000
Our currents can reach up to 12 feet per second. For reference, a fast current is usually about 5 feet per second.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:47.300
And we have tall coastal bluffs that erode and provide sediment. We have wide, high-energy ocean-facing beaches.

00:01:47.300 --> 00:01:55.800
And we have an incredibly rich near-shore ecosystem that contains everything from sea stars and cnidarians to our big charismatic orcas,

00:01:55.800 --> 00:02:00.199
which if you've been walking along our shoreline, you may have been lucky enough to see.

00:02:00.199 --> 00:02:05.400
We also have an incredibly developed shoreline. Humans have been in this area for about 13,000 years.

00:02:05.400 --> 00:02:12.399
And when Western settlers came to the area in the 1800s, the shoreline modification changed at a very high rate.

00:02:12.399 --> 00:02:15.600
So a lot of shorelines look very different from how they used to.

00:02:15.600 --> 00:02:24.500
And these modifications interfere with natural processes that include erosion and beach building and habitat formation.

00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:31.100
So some of these modifications have produced some pretty serious conflicts between man and world.

00:02:31.100 --> 00:02:38.500
So one example I'm going to show you of that is the town of North Cove, which is about three and a half hours southwest of here.

00:02:38.500 --> 00:02:47.600
This is the town of North Cove from satellite in 1995. And then just 10 years later, this is what it looks like.

00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:57.300
And then in 2020, it looked something like this. So we lost 3,000 feet of shoreline in just 25 years.

00:02:57.300 --> 00:03:00.100
At the highest rate, it was 100 feet per year.

00:03:00.100 --> 00:03:03.899
And I have visited this site and the houses are literally falling into the sea.

00:03:03.899 --> 00:03:14.600
So it is important that we know what is going to happen to our shorelines and have some tools to help defend and mitigate some of the risks that our coastal communities face.

00:03:14.600 --> 00:03:16.899
At this point, you may be wondering if you are at the correct conference.

00:03:16.899 --> 00:03:19.699
This is an open science or open data science talk.

00:03:19.699 --> 00:03:27.399
And this is a use case about how we used open science to make hydrodynamic modeling software more accessible to our coastal communities.

00:03:27.399 --> 00:03:32.899
So this project was in Bellingham at a site called Clayton Beach.

00:03:32.899 --> 00:03:37.399
And that's about 80 miles north of where we are now. It's like an hour and a half drive.

00:03:37.399 --> 00:03:44.000
So this is Clayton Beach. It's a really popular spot for locals to go picnic and be by the water.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:48.000
It's a very beautiful spot. It is also heavily modified.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:54.199
So in the late 18th century, the Great Northern Railroad was built along this site.

00:03:54.199 --> 00:03:58.899
And that involves a lot of shoreline modifications and armoring.

00:03:58.899 --> 00:04:08.100
So a big hydraulic trench was dredged offshore and rock was blasted out of the side of the Chuckanut Formation, which is the rock type that we have up there.

00:04:08.100 --> 00:04:16.500
And all of that side cast fill was blasted out back into the water and invariably brought back to the beach from our currents.

00:04:16.500 --> 00:04:23.299
So that resulted in this sort of false armoring and a heavily modified shoreline that remains to this day.

00:04:23.299 --> 00:04:27.100
So on the left, there's that 1800s picture. And from the right, that's from 2022.

00:04:27.100 --> 00:04:31.600
So you can still see all of that rock and the old pilings are still there.

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:40.399
So our job with this project was to try and understand how we could restore the beach within our stakeholder resources from a natural approach.

00:04:40.399 --> 00:04:44.700
So this photo is Clayton Beach taken from drone in 2006.

00:04:44.700 --> 00:04:52.200
And that red line you're seeing is armoring that was put in place when erosion reached too close to comfort for the railroad that curves near the beach.

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:57.000
In 2006, that was 50 feet. And in 2016, it was 150.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:04.700
So we're entering this cycle of erosion and armoring and erosion and armoring, and we wanted to try and find a better way.

00:05:04.700 --> 00:05:11.899
So how we're going to do this is run hydrodynamic modeling over engineering surfaces that our engineers came up with.

00:05:11.899 --> 00:05:17.000
And once we have the surfaces, we can identify areas of high risk.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:22.700
So Clayton Beach is exposed to a very high fetch, which is the distance over which waves can develop.

00:05:22.700 --> 00:05:26.700
It is openly accessed through the Strait of Juan Fuca.

00:05:26.700 --> 00:05:35.200
And there are mountain ranges that surround us, creating variable wind patterns and a lot of things that we needed to account for in our models.

00:05:35.200 --> 00:05:37.600
So this is what a model domain looks like.

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:44.600
This is called a SWAN model, which computes random short crested wind generated waves in a hypothetical environment.

00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:49.600
You're looking at depth there and energy dissipation over a certain space.

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:52.899
And these models can do everything that real waves would do.

00:05:52.899 --> 00:06:02.100
So shoaling as they hit the bottom, refraction, changing the waves around items that they might hit, white capping, reflection, transmission,

00:06:02.100 --> 00:06:05.399
all of these wave behaviors can be modeled in the software.

00:06:05.399 --> 00:06:10.799
In other words, it can basically tell you what your sandcastle is going to look like by the afternoon.

00:06:10.799 --> 00:06:15.100
These are the shallow water equations. This is how this modeling software works.

00:06:15.100 --> 00:06:19.500
This describes the movement of fluid under a free surface with low viscosity.

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:25.000
And when you put these models into the real world, they start to describe the action of real waves.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:30.399
So this is called a wave breaking, which is kind of like a person walking in the trip and their head goes over their heels.

00:06:30.399 --> 00:06:33.299
So the top of the wave is moving faster than the bottom.

00:06:33.299 --> 00:06:37.799
And once we have these equations, we put them over a geographic grid.

00:06:37.799 --> 00:06:43.000
And then those equations are run in space and time over the grid.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:50.299
So what this ends up looking like, on the right hand side, you have a flat surface that's being modeled within a bathtub scenario.

00:06:50.299 --> 00:06:53.200
The water equations are run across that surface.

00:06:53.200 --> 00:06:58.500
And then all of that refracting and changing of the water is handled by the modeling software.

00:06:58.500 --> 00:07:02.700
On the left hand side, you can see the waves are moving along that coastline.

00:07:02.700 --> 00:07:06.700
When they hit the man-made armoring structure at the top, they refract around the sides.

00:07:06.700 --> 00:07:12.000
So this is just visualizing what those mathematics are doing.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:15.000
So back to our site. There's Clayton Beach up on the right hand side.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:20.700
And here's the entire modeling domain that is containing the site where the mathematics will be run.

00:07:20.700 --> 00:07:24.399
And if you remember this fun gif from earlier, it really does look something like this.

00:07:24.399 --> 00:07:28.000
These waves are running over a computational grid.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:33.000
Fortunately for us, the modeling software handles all of that mathematics internally,

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:37.700
because otherwise that would be a lot of math to do for that space.

00:07:37.700 --> 00:07:41.500
So what do these models look like and what goes into them?

00:07:41.500 --> 00:07:45.899
For the ones for Clayton Beach, we had three separate oceanographic conditions,

00:07:45.899 --> 00:07:51.000
times four engineering surfaces, times nine timestamps of runtime,

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:55.799
which gives us about 108 potential scenarios that we were running over this beach.

00:07:55.799 --> 00:08:01.299
For each one of those scenarios, we have 28 hydrodynamic variables of interest.

00:08:01.299 --> 00:08:08.899
And if any of you can do math very quickly, you'll see that is 3,024 individual items that we need to pull out manually.

00:08:08.899 --> 00:08:16.000
So if I have an action per minute of two clicks per second, that's about half an hour, which is not that bad.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:19.600
You can do that manually. A carpal tunnel is fine.

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:24.700
But we're always asking new questions. What if we filled in that trench that's dredged offshore?

00:08:24.700 --> 00:08:29.200
What if we add more groynes and try to shift that sediment transport?

00:08:29.200 --> 00:08:32.200
What if we restore the eelgrass and if we have funding for that?

00:08:32.200 --> 00:08:37.000
And each time we do this, we have to rerun the models and extract everything again.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:43.400
And pretty soon you have this rapidly expanding database of sort of similarly named things that you have to query and organize.

00:08:43.400 --> 00:08:50.000
And there's a better way. So introducing the open science part of this.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:55.000
So instead of using the manual traditional hydrodynamics software,

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:58.900
I used X-Ray and exported everything as a net CDF,

00:08:58.900 --> 00:09:06.700
which is kind of a portable, self-describing data structure that's really common in scientific data types.

00:09:06.700 --> 00:09:10.200
So using X-Ray and that modeling platform that we were talking about earlier,

00:09:10.200 --> 00:09:16.900
that all is being combined into a single array that is now easily queryable.

00:09:16.900 --> 00:09:22.099
Another package that was really helpful was CartaPy. CartaPy places those modeling outputs in space.

00:09:22.099 --> 00:09:30.400
So we can see where the energy dissipation, those hydrodynamic modeling variables I was talking about earlier, we can see where they're happening.

00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:33.000
So this is an export of those two things combined.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:39.200
The X-Ray multidimensional array over CartaPy and that's over Clayton Beach.

00:09:39.200 --> 00:09:47.900
So you can see the depth just displayed. And I did that with a single script and a single click out of those 3,024 extractions.

00:09:47.900 --> 00:09:55.000
So zooming in on this image, you can see the red dot on that right hand side was an area of high erosion risk.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:10:02.099
And so we extracted data from that point and then we could start plotting it and asking questions about it.

00:10:02.099 --> 00:10:08.799
So the existing dredged surface, this is energy dissipation as wave height increases.

00:10:08.799 --> 00:10:14.900
So you can see that as time goes up, the wave height is increasing and the dissipation itself is increasing.

00:10:14.900 --> 00:10:18.500
So small waves do not carry a lot of energy.

00:10:18.500 --> 00:10:23.400
You can't really transport anything on them and you're not really going to face much of an erosion risk.

00:10:23.400 --> 00:10:30.599
But as those waves grow in height, they are transporting a lot of energy and that energy is being imparted into the sediments resulting in erosion.

00:10:30.599 --> 00:10:36.500
So we knew that wave height was a problem. But what happens if we restore the surface?

00:10:36.500 --> 00:10:40.400
Now with a naturally restored and filled surface created by our engineers,

00:10:40.400 --> 00:10:43.799
we can see that with increasing wave height that dissipation itself is way lower.

00:10:43.799 --> 00:10:50.900
So we have some data now about what restoration we might be able to do.

00:10:50.900 --> 00:10:56.400
And we can do that across any variable. That was for energy dissipation, but we can also do wave steepness.

00:10:56.400 --> 00:11:05.200
Wave steepness is what I was talking about earlier. As that wave starts to break, it trips over itself and high steep waves impart a lot of energy.

00:11:05.200 --> 00:11:16.500
So you can see on that left hand side, it's a little dark, but that dark level and the dark color is indicating that the natural breaking of waves as they hit the shoreline wasn't happening over that dredged area.

00:11:16.500 --> 00:11:22.200
The waves never felt the bottom. So instead, that high dissipation energy was happening right on shore.

00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:28.700
But when we restored the conditions, that breaking of energy is being dissipated across the whole beach

00:11:28.700 --> 00:11:35.599
and we are not having this high energy spot where the waves are breaking and becoming really steep.

00:11:35.599 --> 00:11:40.500
So this is great and all, but I'm fundamentally an R user and I needed the power of ggplot as well.

00:11:40.500 --> 00:11:51.400
So Python helped me leverage that data from a spatial approach to a more temporal approach and just more flexibility of graphs altogether.

00:11:51.400 --> 00:12:00.700
There's Clayton Meach zooming in on that spot. These are two transects that we extracted so we can replace time on the x-axis with geography on the x-axis.

00:12:00.700 --> 00:12:08.599
And we can see snapshots of time on a spatial approach.

00:12:08.599 --> 00:12:14.099
So ggplot, which I love, this is those two profiles that we were looking at.

00:12:14.099 --> 00:12:22.000
So on the left-hand side, you can see the bathymetry of that dredged trench from those two extracted profiles.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:27.700
And that's showing offshore dredged. When we fill in that offshore dredged with our engineering surfaces,

00:12:27.700 --> 00:12:35.200
we can see now that the bathymetry is a lot more natural, how like a normal beach would look.

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:39.000
And now across those profiles, we can again extract anything we want from those.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:44.200
So this is energy dissipation again, and there's our two profiles.

00:12:44.200 --> 00:12:52.299
And on the top thing, on the top set of graphs here, we have the offshore, the existing beach surface.

00:12:52.299 --> 00:12:59.900
So you can see that that high peak of energy dissipation is happening really close to shore because on the x-axis, we have distance from shore.

00:12:59.900 --> 00:13:04.700
So right on those sensitive onshore structures, we're getting a really high energy dissipation.

00:13:04.700 --> 00:13:10.299
On the bottom, when we fill in the restored beach surface, that energy is shifted offshore.

00:13:10.299 --> 00:13:14.799
So we can never destroy the energy, but we can move it somewhere else.

00:13:14.799 --> 00:13:21.900
And that vertical black line that you're seeing is a reference point for those rocks from the image earlier, that old sidecast fill.

00:13:21.900 --> 00:13:25.799
So we can just actually see that the energy dissipation is being moved away.

00:13:25.799 --> 00:13:32.299
And this was the selling image for our client to convince them that natural restoration is an option.

00:13:32.299 --> 00:13:36.700
Lastly, these kind of results need to be accessible to a lot of different kind of people.

00:13:36.700 --> 00:13:43.700
We have engineers, coastal scientists, government officials, and the coastal communities who are actually dealing with this shoreline change.

00:13:43.700 --> 00:13:46.099
So Cordo ended up being the perfect tool for that.

00:13:46.099 --> 00:13:52.599
I was able to use my R chunks and my Python chunks in addition to all of that extra scientific,

00:13:52.599 --> 00:13:57.500
hydrodynamic information that you need to have to give this kind of work context.

00:13:57.599 --> 00:14:08.900
So it went from that raw version to a nicely rendered sheet that I could pretty much render indefinitely for multiple different audiences with very few clicks.

00:14:08.900 --> 00:14:18.799
And we were able to get a single Cordo document that had all of the information that we needed for any audience that wanted to look at it.

00:14:18.799 --> 00:14:27.599
And everything is looking bright for this field of research because Python is now producing packages that can handle pre-processing as well as post-processing.

00:14:27.599 --> 00:14:33.299
This is output from a package that can render the computational grid automatically instead of doing it by hand,

00:14:33.299 --> 00:14:39.500
which is one of the most time-consuming parts of hydrodynamic modeling is making that grid by hand.

00:14:39.500 --> 00:14:45.099
So these are tools to protect our shorelines for the next generation.

00:14:45.099 --> 00:14:47.900
This is my daughter, Nadia, making a cameo in this.

00:14:48.099 --> 00:14:50.200
Introducing her to shoreline work early.

00:14:50.200 --> 00:15:00.000
But it just makes this previously inaccessible type of work more accessible to lots of different kinds of people and saves us a ton of time as well.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:01.799
So thank you so much for listening to this.

00:15:01.799 --> 00:15:03.700
This is my LinkedIn if you have any questions.

00:15:03.700 --> 00:15:05.299
And I would love to talk to you guys more.

00:15:05.299 --> 00:15:06.700
Thank you so much for listening to my talk.

00:15:18.900 --> 00:15:22.000
All right, a couple of questions.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:26.700
How did you become interested in this data or in this field?

00:15:26.700 --> 00:15:29.599
And how do you see this work developing in the future?

00:15:29.599 --> 00:15:35.299
So my background is in biochemical oceanography and metabolomics in a lab-based setting.

00:15:35.299 --> 00:15:38.200
And I honestly wanted to spend less time at sea.

00:15:38.200 --> 00:15:40.799
So I moved to a more coastal setting.

00:15:41.200 --> 00:15:51.200
And I've always been really interested in wave dynamics and shoreline protection from a natural perspective, watching the shorelines change over Puget Sound for the time that I've lived here.

00:15:51.200 --> 00:15:58.400
So as for where I see this going, I just think that the packages that accompany this kind of modeling are just exploding.

00:15:58.400 --> 00:15:59.799
It's amazing what people are doing.

00:15:59.799 --> 00:16:11.299
And some classic packages like X-Ray and the Tidyverse are playing really nicely with some of the new ones that are doing really complex pre- and post-processing steps for hydrodynamic modeling.

00:16:11.299 --> 00:16:14.000
So I think there's a bright future for this kind of stuff.

00:16:16.400 --> 00:16:22.799
I guess a follow-up to that is how much of this type of work needs to be done by domain experts?

00:16:22.799 --> 00:16:27.400
And how much can it be done by a newly data science graduate?

00:16:28.400 --> 00:16:36.799
I think a lot of the post-processing is pretty much is accessible to pretty much anyone who has a decent understanding of data structures and how they work.

00:16:36.799 --> 00:16:51.799
The modeling and the pre-processing requires a lot of domain expertise to understand where to pull out data for erosion risk areas and understanding of sediment transport to use your resources and the cost of modeling effectively.

00:16:51.799 --> 00:16:53.099
This is a very small model.

00:16:53.099 --> 00:16:55.500
This model took maybe 10 minutes to run.

00:16:55.500 --> 00:17:02.099
I've worked on another that took six hours to run because it uses 3D dynamics and water shearing over time.

00:17:02.099 --> 00:17:06.300
So some of those pre-processing steps require domain expertise.

00:17:06.300 --> 00:17:12.500
But a lot of the analysis and the images that I was showing up there, I'm relatively new to R and Python.

00:17:12.500 --> 00:17:14.900
And I think you guys are probably more experienced.

00:17:14.900 --> 00:17:16.300
So I think it's really accessible.

00:17:19.900 --> 00:17:22.000
I think this is the last question.

00:17:22.099 --> 00:17:25.900
How far in advance do engineers need to interfere with issues like this?

00:17:25.900 --> 00:17:36.099
And how do they keep up with all the different problems along the shore?

00:17:36.099 --> 00:17:37.500
Can you read the first part of the question again?

00:17:37.500 --> 00:17:41.599
How far in advance do engineers need to interfere with issues like this?

00:17:41.599 --> 00:17:44.800
That is often up to the clients.

00:17:44.800 --> 00:17:54.400
The eternal problem with shoreline armoring is that erosion is a natural process, especially here in Puget Sound because of our sedimentary rock formations.

00:17:54.400 --> 00:18:05.099
So there is always a trade-off between natural restoration and what we call hard armoring or bulkhead installation.

00:18:05.099 --> 00:18:12.000
And engineers have to weigh some of the benefits and the pros and cons of hard armoring.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:19.099
One of the effects of hard armoring is the destruction of the habitat that feeds salmon, which has a really big effect on the salmon industry.

00:18:19.099 --> 00:18:22.000
So there are a lot of people and opinions at play.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:25.699
But in general, I would say it depends on the location.

00:18:25.699 --> 00:18:35.500
So anywhere from like a year to if you're in the North Cove location, you know, you have days to think about what you're going to do before the water starts reaching your house.

00:18:35.500 --> 00:18:37.000
All right. Yeah, that's all of our questions.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:38.800
Let's thank Tina one more time.

